# Error Handling

## Express 5 Async Error Handling

Express 5 automatically catches errors thrown in async route handlers and forwards them to the global error middleware. Do NOT wrap handlers in try/catch or `.catch(next)` unless you need to catch a specific error and do something with it before re-throwing.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — unnecessary try/catch
async handleGetBook(req: Request, res: Response) {
  try {
    const book = await BookService.getById(req.params.id);
    sendSuccess(res, book);
  } catch (e) {
    next(e);
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD — let Express 5 catch it automatically
async handleGetBook(req: Request, res: Response) {
  const book = await BookService.getById(req.params.id);
  if (!book) throw new BookNotFoundError(req.params.id);
  sendSuccess(res, book);
}
```

Only use try/catch when you need to handle a specific error locally (e.g. fallback logic, retries, partial error recovery).

## Defining Named Errors

All named errors live in `src/errors/errors.ts`. Extend `Error`, set `this.name`, and use `{ cause }` to preserve the original error.

```typescript
export class BookNotFoundError extends Error {
  public readonly bookId: string;
  constructor(id: string) {
    super(`Book not found: ${id}`);
    this.name = "BookNotFoundError";
    this.bookId = id;
  }
}
```

## Global Error Middleware

`src/middleware/error.middleware.ts` is the Express `ErrorRequestHandler` registered last via `app.use(errorHandler)`. For each named error, use `instanceof` to match, log appropriately, and call `sendError`.

```typescript
if (error instanceof BookNotFoundError) {
  logger.warn(error.message);
  sendError(res, 404, "BOOK_NOT_FOUND", error.message);
  return;
}
```

## Route Registration

Always pass controller methods directly to the router — never wrap them in `(req, res, next) => ...` and never use `.catch(next)`. This applies to both `TypedRouter` and plain `express.Router()`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — wrapper + .catch(next)
router.get("/sync", (req, res, next) => {
  SyncController.beginIdentitySync(req, res).catch(next);
});

// ✅ GOOD — pass method directly
router.get("/sync", SyncController.beginIdentitySync);
```

## Rules

- Every new named error must be added to `src/errors/errors.ts`
- Every new named error must get a corresponding `instanceof` branch in `error.middleware.ts`
- Use `logger.warn` for 4xx (client errors) and `logger.error` for 5xx (server errors)
- Use `sendError(res, status, "CODE", message)` from `src/utils/api-response.ts`
- Controllers never catch-and-respond for domain errors — let them propagate to the global handler
- No `.catch(next)` wrappers in route definitions — Express 5 handles this
- No `(req, res, next) => handler(req, res).catch(next)` wrappers — pass the handler directly
